</section>

<div class="container">
    <div class="row">
        <section id="index-about-heatsavers" class="col-sm-6">
            <h2>Why Do I Need a HeatSaver?</h2>
                <p>
                    Your furnace or heating stove is a wonderful thing in the winter ... BUT, it's not very efficient.
                    Much of the heat escapes out your chimney and heats the outdoors.
                </p>
                <p>
                    A set of Stovepipe HeatSavers will wrap around your stovepipe, conduct the wasted heat from the flue into the bands,
                    and radiate it back into your house, making your furnace or stove much more efficient.  
                    It reclaims energy that would otherwise be lost.
                    It will help you increase the heat going into your house and/or save on your energy bills!
                </p>
        </section>

        <section id="index-how-to-measure" class="col-sm-6">
            <h2>How to Order</h2>
                <h3>Measure the circumference of your stovepipe</h3>
                    <h4>Materials needed</h4>
                        <h5>Method 1 - A flexible tape measure</h5>
                        <ul>
                            <li>If you have a flexible tape measure (like those used for taking clothing measurements), you may use that.</li>
                            <li>Do NOT use a metal tape measure! You will not get a good measurement because it is too rigid.</li>
                        </ul>
                        <h5>Method 2 - A piece of string / yarn and a tape measure or yardstick</h5>
                    <h4>How to Measure</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Do NOT measure a hot stovepipe! Wait until it is cool.</li>
                        <li>Wrap your flexible tape measure or string around the stovepipe, and note where it starts to overlap.</li>
                        <li>If using a flexible tape measure, note the measurement at the point of overlap.</li>
                        <li>If using a string, grasp the string at the exact point of overlap.  
                            Then place the loose end of the string at the beginning (0") of the tape measure,
                            and stretch it tight down the tape measure.  
                            Note the measurement at the point your fingers are grasping the string.</li>
                    </ul>
                <h3>Enter your measurement here</h3>
            <div id="index-find-by-circumference">
                @Html.Partial("_FindByCircumferencePartial")
            </div>

        </section>
    </div>
</div>
